    {
      "block_id": "3354750c-f3ba-80c9-81d5-cf1a256eab87",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Moment of Prediction",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "Final Grade in Course",
          "Normalized Final Score (0 to 1)",
          "21314 undergraduate students",
          "811 unique undergraduate face-to-face courses with LMS support; analysis restricted to large courses (>50 enrollments)",
          "SIS, LMS logs",
          "[AGE, GEND, F_SCHO, HS_CGPA, EX_LEN, EX_MAT, SCHOOL, C_DURA, CRED_S, E_SEM, CGPA, WEB_READ, CONT_READ, SYLL_READ, MSG_READ, MSG_NEW, MSG_REPLY, MSG_FORW, QUIZ_SUB, AS_SUB, AS_REV, SEC_READ, FOR_READ, FOR_RESP, CHAT_NEW, POLL_VOTE, POLL_READ, NEWREAD, WIKI_READ, WIKI_REV, WIKI_NEW, PREF_UPD, PREF_ADD, PROF_PRIV, PROF_PREF]",
          "Mid-semester and end-of-semester; authors compare prediction using only fixed data, full-term LMS data, and midterm LMS data",
          "Data from DARA and SAKAI were integrated into a unified database. Records were cleaned for inconsistencies, recoded into standard formats, and encrypted. LMS actions by the same student of the same type within 60 seconds were collapsed into one action. Courses were filtered into three sets: Large Courses, Large Top 20%, and Large Top 10% according to enrollment size and LMS use. CGPA and LMS usage variables were z-score transformed to improve comparability across courses. Final grades were normalized to 0–1.",
          "Linear Regression, Robust Linear Regression, Random Forest",
          "10-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "{RMSE: 0.0848 – Random Forest, Large Top 10%, M-LMS; RSquared: 0.6736 – Random Forest, Large Top 10%, M-LMS; R-Fscore: 0.5349 – Random Forest, Large Top 10%, M-LMS}\n\n",
          "Main contribution is a centralized, low-cost institutional model for early identification of at-risk students in large classes. Random Forest clearly outperformed Linear Regression and Robust Linear Regression, especially when LMS data were added. Importantly, midterm LMS data performed as well as or slightly better than full-term LMS data, supporting early intervention use. Variable relevance analysis showed CGPA as the strongest predictor, followed by enrolled school; LMS variables had lower but still useful predictive value, improving RMSE by up to 12.28% according to the abstract.\n",
          "Focused only on large face-to-face courses supported by LMS, so results may not generalize to small classes or fully online contexts. LMS variables were mostly low-level aggregated counts and reflected relatively passive LMS use. Prediction still depends strongly on prior academic performance (especially CGPA), which may limit interpretability from a learning-process perspective. The study was conducted in one university with a particular institutional context.\n\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
